Table 1. Molecular Weights (MWs) and Critical Micelle Concentrations (CMCs) of the New Agents and Micelle Sizes (

 R


 h

) (mean ± standard deviation;

 n

= 4) of Their Micelles at Room Temperature

DLS experiments were carried out to measure the size of self-assemblies formed by the SIGs. We found that the assembly sizes were substantially affected by the detergent alkyl chain length. With an increasing alkyl chain length, the detergent self-assembly was substantially enlarged within each set of SIGs. For example, the aggregate sizes of the STM-Es drastically increased from 2.5 to 3.8 to 11.2 to 21.1 nm with an increasing alkyl chain length from C7 to C8 to C9 to C10, respectively. In addition, the detergent assembly size was profoundly influenced by the volumes of the detergent headgroups (SHG-Gs vs STMs/STM-Es). A larger headgroup renders a more conical detergent molecular shape, thereby decreasing the assembly size, as exemplified by a comparison of STM-12 with SHG-G12. Although these two agents have the same alkyl chain length (C12), SHG-G12 with the hexaglucoside headgroup formed much smaller assemblies (2.7 nm) than STM-12 with the trimaltoside headgroup (12.3 nm). Due to the presence of the bulky headgroup (i.e., hexaglucoside), all of the SHG-Gs formed micelles that were smaller (2.7–2.9 nm) than those of DDM (3.4 nm) despite the possession of a long alkyl chain. More interestingly, STM-11 and -12 (9.4 and 12.3 nm, respectively) formed micelles that were smaller than those of STM-E10 (21.1 nm), although these agents have alkyl chains that are longer than that of the latter. This result is unexpected as the headgroup of the STM-Es appears to be larger than that of the STMs due to the presence of the additional ethylene glycol linkers. This unexpected result suggests that the introduction of the flexible ethylene glycol linker allows the three maltose units of the STM-Es to come together, decreasing the effective volume of the headgroup. On the other hand, the three maltose units of the STMs appear to occupy a relatively large volume because of the lack of such a flexible linker. The homogeneity of micelles formed by each new detergent was supported by a single set of size population in its DLS profile (

 Figure S3

)

